Texas Landlord-Tenant Court Caseload: COVID Moratorium Effects (2018–2022)
Tools: R · tidyverse · ggplot2
Data: State landlord-tenant court caseload records, CY 2018–2022, aggregated by county and year

Overview
Analysis of landlord-tenant court activity across five years spanning the COVID-19 eviction moratorium period. The data reveals that moratorium-era protections didn't just suppress filings — they created a massive backlog of inactive, legally-frozen cases that began reactivating at unprecedented rates once protections expired.
Key Findings
New filings dropped sharply in 2020 — then surged past pre-pandemic levels.
New cases filed fell from ~260,000 in 2019 to ~140,000 in 2020, a drop of roughly 45%. By 2022, filings had rebounded to nearly 280,000 — exceeding any prior year in the dataset. The moratorium suppressed filings; its expiration unleashed them.
Inactive cases accumulated continuously throughout the moratorium.
While filings fell, inactive cases end-of-month climbed steadily from ~29,000 in 2018 to ~65,000 by 2022 — more than doubling. The steepest growth occurred between 2020 and 2021, as cases were filed, stayed, and could not be resolved. This backlog represents legally active but procedurally frozen cases that courts and tenants had to absorb post-moratorium.
Active caseload spiked in 2021 and remained elevated.
Active cases end-of-month jumped from ~1.135M in 2020 to ~1.205M in 2021 — a significant single-year increase — and held near that level into 2022, reflecting the system struggling to process accumulated demand.
Case reactivations exploded post-moratorium.
Cases reactivated held flat below 500/year from 2018–2020, then surged to ~2,500 in 2021 and ~2,700 in 2022 — a 5x increase. This is the clearest signal of the moratorium's mechanical effect: cases weren't resolved, they were paused, and they came back.
Appeals rose sharply in 2022 across both pathways.
Both cases appealed after trial (~12,500 in 2022 vs. ~5,300 pre-pandemic) and cases appealed without trial (~3,700 in 2022 vs. ~2,400 pre-pandemic) hit multi-year highs, suggesting post-moratorium disputes were more contested and legally complex than typical caseloads.
Caseload concentration varies significantly by county.
Sorting total new cases filed by county reveals high geographic concentration — a small number of counties account for a disproportionate share of total filings, consistent with population distribution and urban rental market density.
Methods

Loaded multi-year CSV of landlord-tenant court records by county
Grouped by year and summed all numeric columns to produce statewide annual totals
Generated line plots for all 20 numeric variables to identify trends
Grouped by county to rank total new cases filed across the full period

Data Source
State court administrative records — Landlord Tenant Caseload CY 2018–2022
